<p><b>Crowd psychology</b> is a branch of <a href="/wiki/Social_psychology" title="Social psychology">social psychology</a>. Ordinary people can typically gain direct power by acting collectively. Historically, because large <a href="/wiki/Group_(sociology)" title="Group (sociology)" class="mw-redirect">groups of people</a> have been able to bring about dramatic and sudden social change in a manner that bypasses established <a href="/wiki/Due_process" title="Due process">due process</a>, they have also provoked controversy. Social scientists have developed several different theories for explaining <a href="/wiki/Crowd" title="Crowd">crowd</a> psychology, and the ways in which the <a href="/wiki/Psychology" title="Psychology">psychology</a> of the crowd differs significantly from the psychology of those individuals within it. <a href="/wiki/Carl_Jung" title="Carl Jung">Carl Jung</a> coined the notion of the <a href="/wiki/Collective_unconscious" title="Collective unconscious">Collective unconscious</a>. Other major thinkers of crowd psychology include <a href="/wiki/Gustave_Le_Bon" title="Gustave Le Bon">Gustave Le Bon</a>, <a href="/wiki/Wilfred_Trotter" title="Wilfred Trotter">Wilfred Trotter</a>, <a href="/wiki/Gabriel_Tarde" title="Gabriel Tarde">Gabriel Tarde</a>, <a href="/wiki/Sigmund_Freud" title="Sigmund Freud">Sigmund Freud</a> and <a href="/wiki/Elias_Canetti" title="Elias Canetti">Elias Canetti</a>.</p>
